{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568539"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:17:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:17:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20989"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20989"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.17,0.75,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103315"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13864"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20989"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85734"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4112"},{"type":"tags","id":"4141"},{"type":"tags","id":"4179"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"9750"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"13336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44662"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103315"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of pelvic heaviness and a dragging sensation in her vagina. She reports occasional difficulty emptying her bladder completely. Her symptoms worsen after prolonged standing and towards the end of the day. She has given birth to three children vaginally, the youngest being five years ago. Her medical history includes mild asthma and seasonal allergies. She takes salbutamol inhaler as needed and a daily antihistamine. She works as a primary school teacher and reports lifting heavy boxes of books regularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Pelvic examination reveals a grade 1 cystocele that reduces when she is lying down. There is no evidence of rectocele or uterine prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Watchful waiting with annual review","Referral to gynaecologist for vaginal pessary fitting","Referral for supervised pelvic floor muscle physiotherapy","Referral to gynaecologist for surgical repair","Commence oestrogen cream application twice weekly"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with pelvic organ prolapse (POP), specifically a grade 1 cystocele. Her symptoms of pelvic heaviness, vaginal dragging sensation, and bladder symptoms are classic for this condition. Given the mild nature of her prolapse and her relatively young age, conservative management is most appropriate initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for supervised pelvic floor muscle physiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended first-line treatment for women with mild pelvic organ prolapse, based on high level evidence (NHMRC Level 1 evidence). Pelvic floor muscle training (PFMT) involves regular exercises to strengthen the pelvic floor muscles, improving their ability to support pelvic organs. A structured programme typically includes assessment, specific exercises (8-12 repetitions of 6-8 second contractions, 1-3 times daily), and learning the \u0027Knack\u0027 manoeuvre (contracting pelvic floor muscles before and during activities that increase intra-abdominal pressure). Evidence shows that supervised PFMT over 3-6 months can significantly improve prolapse symptoms and potentially reduce the severity of anatomical prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting with annual review\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered for asymptomatic or minimally symptomatic prolapse, but this patient has symptoms affecting her quality of life, warranting active intervention rather than observation alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to gynaecologist for vaginal pessary fitting\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable alternative for women who cannot or do not wish to perform PFMT, or for those with more severe prolapse. However, it would not be considered first-line before attempting PFMT in this patient with a mild, reducible grade 1 cystocele.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to gynaecologist for surgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature at this stage. Surgery is typically reserved for women with more severe prolapse, those who have failed conservative management, or those with significant impact on quality of life. Given the risks associated with surgical intervention and the potential for recurrence, conservative approaches should be exhausted first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence oestrogen cream application twice weekly\u003C/strong\u003E may be beneficial in postmenopausal women with vaginal atrophy contributing to prolapse symptoms, but there is no indication this patient is postmenopausal or has vaginal atrophy. Topical oestrogen alone is not an effective treatment for the mechanical issues of prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to PFMT, this patient would benefit from lifestyle modifications including weight management if needed, avoiding heavy lifting, treating constipation, and learning to brace her pelvic floor during activities that increase intra-abdominal pressure. A physiotherapist specialising in women\u0027s health would be the appropriate provider to supervise her PFMT programme.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pelvic organ prolapse symptoms include pelvic heaviness, vaginal dragging sensation, visible bulge, backache, and bladder/bowel symptoms.","Regular, supervised pelvic floor muscle training over 3-6 months is more effective than self-directed exercises for mild to moderate vaginal prolapse."],"references":["The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Pelvic floor muscle training: pelvic organ prolapse. East Melbourne, VIC: RACGP; 2014 Nov. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/a-z/p/pelvic-floor-muscle-training-pelvic-organ-prolapse","Dietz HP. Pelvic organ prolapse \u2013 a review. Aust Fam Physician. 2015 Jul;44(7):446\u201352. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/july/pelvic-organ-prolapse-a-review"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85734"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20989"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85734"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T14:02:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T14:03:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13864"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103315"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"typ